  public void display() {
    System.out.println("Alpha");
  }
}

class Bravo() <<<extends Alpha>>> {
  public void display() {
    System.out.println("Bravo");
    super.display();
  }
}

class Charlie() <<<extends Alpha>>> {
  public void display() {
    System.out.println("Charlie");
    super.display();
  }
}

class Delta <<<extends Charlie>>> () {
  public void display() {
    System.out.println("Delta");
    super.display();
  }
}
```

* The `b` object runs the `display` method which prints `Bravo`. 
* The next line of output is `Alpha` which means `super` refers to class `Alpha`. Therefore, class `Bravo` extends class `Alpha`.
* The `d` object runs the `display` method which prints `Delta`. However, there are two more lines of output. That means class `Delta` has multilevel inheritance.
* The next line of output is `Charlie` which means `super` refers to class `Charlie`. Therefore, class `Delta` extends class `Charlie`.
* Finally, calling `display` in class `Charlie` must also print `Alpha`. That means class `Charlie` extends class `Alpha`.

